# Console font — atlas
#
# This is what sizes the ly greeter. ly's big clock is drawn as a 5x5 grid of
# U+2593 cells per digit (ly-ui/src/components/BigLabel.zig, CHAR_WIDTH =
# CHAR_HEIGHT = 5), and that 5x5 is fixed. The console font's cell size is
# therefore the ONLY control over how big the clock is:
#
#   default8x16   ->  digit  40x80 px,  clock 192x80 px   (the kernel default)
#   ter-u24b      ->  digit  60x120 px, clock 288x120 px
#   solar24x32    ->  digit 120x160 px, clock 576x160 px
#
# ter-u24b matches what kronos runs (12x24 Terminus) so the two greeters agree,
# and unlike solar24x32's 24px-wide cells it leaves the greeter's TEXT normally
# proportioned instead of stretched.
#
# Note kronos itself sets ter-v24n, which is the CODEPAGE variant and does NOT
# carry U+2593 -- so kronos's own big clock has no glyph to draw with. ter-u24b
# is the Unicode sibling: same family, same 12x24 cell, glyph present.
#
# CAREFUL if you ever change this: the font MUST carry U+2593 or the clock
# renders as blanks. Most Terminus console faces do NOT -- the codepage
# variants (ter-v32b, ter-1xx, ter-c32b, ...) ship U+2588/2591/2592 but not
# 2593. Only the Unicode variants (ter-uXXb) do. Check before switching:
#
#   zcat /usr/share/consolefonts/<font>.psf*.gz > /tmp/f.psf
#   psfgettable /tmp/f.psf | grep U+2593
#
# ter-u24b comes from media-fonts/terminus-font, which phases/10-packages.sh
# installs for exactly this reason. If that package is ever dropped, the
# consolefont service silently falls back to the 8x16 default and the clock
# shrinks -- so the two belong together.
consolefont="ter-u24b"
